04495nam a22005535i 9780822398042DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223980427 a10.1515/97808223980422doi  a(DE-B1597)553380  a(OCoLC)1125855044  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1978.I53bS43 1996 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a791.5/31 aSears, Laurie J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShadows of Empire :bColonial Discourse and Javanese Tales /cLaurie J. Sears. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b23 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Spelling and Translations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Histories, Mythologies, and Javanese Tales -- tIntroduction Histories, Mythologies, and Javanese Tales -- t2 Colonial Discourse and Javanese Shadow Theatre -- t3 Failed Narratives of the Nation or the New "Essence" of Java? -- t4 Javanese Storytellers, Colonial Categories, Mahabharata Tales -- t5 Revolutionary Rhetoric and Postcolonial Performance Domains -- t6 Fiction, Images, and Allegories -- tSelected Glossary -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShadows of Empire explores Javanese shadow theater as a staging area for negotiations between colonial power and indigenous traditions. Charting the shifting boundaries between myth and history in Javanese Mahabharata and Ramayana tales, Laurie J. Sears reveals what happens when these stories move from village performances and palace manuscripts into colonial texts and nationalist journals and, most recently, comic books and novels. Historical, anthropological, and literary in its method and insight, this work offers a dramatic reassessment of both Javanese literary/theatrical production and Dutch scholarship on Southeast Asia.Though Javanese shadow theater (wayang) has existed for hundreds of years, our knowledge of its history, performance practice, and role in Javanese society only begins with Dutch documentation and interpretation in the nineteenth century. Analyzing the Mahabharata and Ramayana tales in relation to court poetry, Islamic faith, Dutch scholarship, and nationalist journals, Sears shows how the shadow theater as we know it today must be understood as a hybrid of Javanese and Dutch ideas and interests, inseparable from a particular colonial moment. In doing so, she contributes to a re-envisioning of European histories that acknowledges the influence of Asian, African, and New World cultures on European thought-and to a rewriting of colonial and postcolonial Javanese histories that questions the boundaries and content of history and story, myth and allegory, colonialism and culture.Shadows of Empire will appeal not only to specialists in Javanese culture and historians of Indonesia, but also to a wide range of scholars in the areas of performance and literature, anthropology, Southeast Asian studies, and postcolonial studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aTaleszIndonesiazJavaxHistory and criticism. 0aWayang playsxHistory and criticism. 0aWayang. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398042zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398042423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822398042.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles